<dl id="n34001d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34001d">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34001d"> 1(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> monophysic <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n34001d"><li>FW 156.11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fc/lexfc.htm#n34001d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fc/l39fc.htm#n34001d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n34001d">MS Yale 9.3-*7a</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:217 <a name="fcd6" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fcd6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fc/fcd6.htm#n34001d">Draft: I.6&sect;3.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The Council of Chalcedon (451), the fourth oecumenical, declared that Christ is to be acknowledged &ldquo;in two natures&mdash;unconfusedly, unchangeably,&rdquo; and therefore decided against the opinions of all who either believed that the divinity is the sole nature of Christ, or who, rejecting this, taught only one composite nature of Christ (one nature and one person, instead of two natures and one person). The advocates of the one-nature theory were called <mark>Monophysites</mark> &hellip; <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 334 [Controversies and Schisms]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Entry initially transferred to text block on <a name="n34026c" href="n34all.htm#n34026c">N34 (VI.B.27):026(c)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
